<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="232" type="collection and habitat data">
<paragraph pageId="17" pageNumber="232">Collection and habitat data.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="17" pageNumber="232">
Adults of this species were captured in Lindgren funnel traps deployed in an old red oak stand, an old (180-year-old) red pine stand, a mature (110-year-old) red spruce forest, and an old mixed forest. 
<bibRefCitation author="Majka, CG" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="20" pageNumber="235" pagination="45 - 68" title="Understanding saproxylic beetles: new records of Tetratomidae, Melandryidae, Synchroidae, and Scraptiidae from the Maritime provinces of Canada (Coleoptera: Tenebrionoidea)." volume="1248" year="2006">Majka and Pollock (2006)</bibRefCitation>
reported that this species was associated with balsam fir, red spruce, and white pine. In New Brunswick, 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" genus="Phloeotrya" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phloeotrya fusca" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="232" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fusca">Phloeotrya fusca</taxonomicName>
was collected during July and August.
</paragraph>
